Mobile network operator Rain has officially launched 5G in parts of Durban, two years after it had initially planned to roll out in South Africa’s third-biggest city. The company told MyBroadband Rain 5G is now live in the following areas in the Durban metro: The official rollout comes after the operator previously said it was targeting a 5G launch in Durban in 2020. The addition of Durban comes several months after Rain 5G rolled out in smaller cities and towns in 2021, including Potchefstroom, Paarl, Klerksdorp, Rustenburg, and Polokwane. As part of its greater 5G strategy, Rain said it would continue to expand 5G coverage in Durban daily, as well as in the rest of KwaZulu-Natal, Mpumalanga, Free State, Gauteng and Western Cape. The screenshot below shows Rain 5G coverage areas in Durban Central, Durban North, Durban South, and surrounds. Rain previously said it planned to launch 5G in 15 new towns and cities in South Africa in the first half of 2022. The operator secured 40MHz of high-demand radio frequency spectrum during Icasa’s spectrum auction earlier in March, costing just over R1.43 billion. In its results for the six months ended December 2021, Rain’s holding company, ARC Investments, said this would “significantly enhance” the operator’s competitiveness. Rain offers three uncapped fixed 5G packages, with speeds and prices as follows: